object-oriented programming in python?
Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) is a programming paradigm based on classes and objects, where real-world entities are represented using properties (attributes) and behaviors (methods).

The four main pillars of OOP are:

Encapsulation: Wrapping data and methods into a single unit (class) and restricting direct access to data.
Inheritance: Allowing one class (child) to acquire properties and methods from another class (parent), which promotes code reuse.
Polymorphism: The ability of an object to take multiple forms, such as method overloading or method overriding.
Abstraction: Hiding implementation details and showing only essential features to the user.”

static method vs class method in python?
A static method is a method defined inside a class using the @staticmethod decorator. It does not take self or cls as parameters and cannot directly access instance or class variables. It is used when the method does not depend on class or instance data.

A class method is defined using the @classmethod decorator and takes cls as its first parameter. It can access and modify class-level variables and is used when we want to work with the class rather than individual instances.

GIL in python?
The Global Interpreter Lock (GIL) is a mechanism in Python that allows only one thread to execute Python bytecode at a time within a single process.

This is mainly used to ensure thread safety and simplify memory management in CPython. Because of the GIL, even in a multi-threaded program, only one thread runs at a time for CPU-bound tasks, which limits true parallelism.”

init method in python?
The __init__ method in Python is a special method, also known as a constructor. It is automatically called when an object of a class is created. It is used to initialize instance variables of the class. The first parameter is always self, which refers to the current instance


